{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-chapter-level-2-chapter-level-2-tsx","path":"/topics/pubic-lice/diagnosis/assessment/","result":{"pageContext":{"chapter":{"id":"f057204e-4214-5cf6-9912-7bb860065936","slug":"assessment","fullItemName":"Assessment","depth":2,"htmlHeader":"<!-- begin field 9740a342-024d-4000-8af1-4eb0a2213ae5 --><h2>How should I assess a person with suspected pubic lice infestation?</h2><!-- end field 9740a342-024d-4000-8af1-4eb0a2213ae5 -->","summary":"","htmlStringContent":"<!-- begin item 76016d29-5197-4801-afac-4af2eddd4af1 --><!-- begin field 53cd458c-d1a5-4683-bbdc-0937246f9ddd --><ul><li><strong>Take a history asking about:</strong><ul><li>Pruritus — pubic lice infestation commonly presents as genital pruritus which is worse at night.<ul><li>Pruritus may occasionally be localised to other infested areas or generalised.</li></ul></li><li>Visible lice ('crab'-shaped, grey-brown in colour, and about 2 mm in length) or eggs (yellow/white in colour and smaller than a pinhead).</li><li>Other possible sexually transmitted infections.<ul><li>For more information see the CKS topics on <a class=\"topic-reference external-reference\" href=\"/topics/bacterial-vaginosis/\">Bacterial vaginosis</a>, <a class=\"topic-reference external-reference\" href=\"/topics/chlamydia-uncomplicated-genital/\">Chlamydia - uncomplicated genital</a>, <a class=\"topic-reference external-reference\" href=\"/topics/gonorrhoea/\">Gonorrhoea</a>, <a class=\"topic-reference external-reference\" href=\"/topics/hiv-infection-aids/\">HIV infection and AIDS</a>, <a class=\"topic-reference external-reference\" href=\"/topics/syphilis/\">Syphilis</a>, <a class=\"topic-reference external-reference\" href=\"/topics/trichomoniasis/\">Trichomoniasis</a>, <a class=\"topic-reference external-reference\" href=\"/topics/vaginal-discharge/\">Vaginal discharge</a>, and <a class=\"topic-reference external-reference\" href=\"/topics/urethritis-male/\">Urethritis - male</a>.</li></ul></li></ul></li><li><strong>Examine the person looking for:</strong><ul><li>Adult lice and/or nits — a dermatoscope, magnifying lens or fine toothed comb may aid identification.<ul><li>As pubic lice may be found in any coarse hair, all hairy parts of the body should be examined.</li></ul></li><li>Other <a class=\"topic-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/pubic-lice/diagnosis/clinical-features/\">clinical signs</a> of infestation such as small blue macules and red papules at feeding sites, excoriation of the skin and louse faeces (rust coloured specks) on skin and underwear.</li><li>Secondary infections of the skin such as impetigo or cellulitis.</li><li>Signs of chronic infestation such as thickened or hyperpigmented skin.</li></ul></li><li><strong>Pubic lice infestation is usually a clinical diagnosis and investigations are not generally required</strong>.</li></ul><!-- end field 53cd458c-d1a5-4683-bbdc-0937246f9ddd --><!-- end item 76016d29-5197-4801-afac-4af2eddd4af1 -->","topic":{"id":"d9c800be-d493-5d1c-81c1-7e9ac00d0e91","topicId":"01c7ac76-ef6e-42b7-836c-ff538154f62a","topicName":"Pubic lice","slug":"pubic-lice","lastRevised":"Last revised in February 2018","chapters":[{"id":"e84df283-1ddd-5fec-bb06-50027c460ccb","fullItemName":"Summary","slug":"summary","subChapters":[]},{"id":"b002a6cc-4c38-5629-b392-ddb39ece58b7","fullItemName":"Have I got the right topic?","slug":"have-i-got-the-right-topic","subChapters":[]},{"id":"8c0a40c3-6240-572e-91c8-9c9832c437f7","fullItemName":"How up-to-date is this topic?","slug":"how-up-to-date-is-this-topic","subChapters":[{"id":"75c14179-33ce-5f2a-811b-f8d43efb1dff","slug":"changes","fullItemName":"Changes"},{"id":"7251900b-7e07-51b6-9864-ce5feacb2549","slug":"update","fullItemName":"Update"}]},{"id":"9f11ff42-e98f-52ed-ad50-7ccb91b78747","fullItemName":"Goals and outcome measures","slug":"goals-outcome-measures","subChapters":[{"id":"48aa5dc5-ebb5-5204-9cce-98fa93e1fffe","slug":"goals","fullItemName":"Goals"},{"id":"7a514fc4-ac3c-5ece-bdb5-72cb57102cab","slug":"outcome-measures","fullItemName":"Outcome measures"},{"id":"6b51f8aa-d337-50c3-84ee-7ddb0ec0a260","slug":"audit-criteria","fullItemName":"Audit criteria"},{"id":"4d7ae4f3-6c68-5774-afc7-f19a2b8d9bab","slug":"qof-indicators","fullItemName":"QOF indicators"},{"id":"ed24dd27-d5d8-5cfe-a3a9-6231ea4cb3c7","slug":"qipp-options-for-local-implementation","fullItemName":"QIPP - Options for local implementation"},{"id":"df2f4d4f-6204-559a-8620-c66f9e707fe5","slug":"nice-quality-standards","fullItemName":"NICE quality standards"}]},{"id":"48e97107-2ed4-5dbe-8783-e6a4ad841f4f","fullItemName":"Background information","slug":"background-information","subChapters":[{"id":"0a849f5f-c58d-5123-b67a-2ed2ed5785e2","slug":"cause","fullItemName":"Cause"},{"id":"d0334bc2-4df2-5845-bce2-445965f164f0","slug":"prevalence","fullItemName":"Prevalence"},{"id":"552d4381-4bfc-56d9-af49-28846d287c6f","slug":"complications","fullItemName":"Complications"},{"id":"f13fad18-e14e-5cfa-ae13-286bd9a1c0d7","slug":"prognosis","fullItemName":"Prognosis"}]},{"id":"0c522f07-ff65-5f92-b30a-dcfc2729a67c","fullItemName":"Diagnosis","slug":"diagnosis","subChapters":[{"id":"d1bedd68-5e95-5663-a152-06c967e39c73","slug":"clinical-features","fullItemName":"Clinical features"},{"id":"f057204e-4214-5cf6-9912-7bb860065936","slug":"assessment","fullItemName":"Assessment"},{"id":"b064b8e0-34ee-5def-a173-fac1c1c12b37","slug":"differential-diagnosis","fullItemName":"Differential diagnosis"}]},{"id":"dae71d97-8464-5ce8-9069-b5dbfdd59c76","fullItemName":"Management","slug":"management","subChapters":[{"id":"5c26dadb-4955-504f-bc48-288de88e0e36","slug":"management","fullItemName":"Scenario: Management"}]},{"id":"b421d0c6-16e3-5df9-a4f1-d872420d92a0","fullItemName":"Prescribing information","slug":"prescribing-information","subChapters":[{"id":"b612b27c-a557-5c2d-b4e8-3cf05ed304f5","slug":"permethrin","fullItemName":"Permethrin"},{"id":"c3bf4214-4db9-5aed-9e8f-f26920bbc30f","slug":"malathion","fullItemName":"Malathion"}]},{"id":"de2fbc3d-85e6-5885-a5ed-8656ba93c16b","fullItemName":"Supporting evidence","slug":"supporting-evidence","subChapters":[]},{"id":"6d9374ee-83e0-59cf-becb-e16b8ccd36be","fullItemName":"How this topic was developed","slug":"how-this-topic-was-developed","subChapters":[{"id":"52d45c19-1905-5e75-b344-8f3e9c345e28","slug":"search-strategy","fullItemName":"Search strategy"},{"id":"f9ddc530-3fa3-534f-8e36-4aa5e205a451","slug":"stakeholder-engagement","fullItemName":"Stakeholder engagement"},{"id":"a235b485-afab-5962-a532-dc753485e1f1","slug":"evidence-exclusion-criteria","fullItemName":"Evidence exclusion criteria"},{"id":"8aaf6bed-e5b8-54fc-8d1a-1546cba416fe","slug":"organizational-behavioural-financial-barriers","fullItemName":"Organizational, behavioural and financial barriers"},{"id":"e5533b71-1715-5937-8266-a8fc60feb025","slug":"declarations-of-interest","fullItemName":"Declarations of interest"}]},{"id":"27ce50e8-aa96-5e1d-b770-65a8e2b03760","fullItemName":"References","slug":"references","subChapters":[]}]},"parentChapter":{"id":"0c522f07-ff65-5f92-b30a-dcfc2729a67c","slug":"diagnosis","fullItemName":"Diagnosis"},"subChapters":[{"id":"69720160-7d80-5940-b826-1b3c85e903a1","slug":"basis-for-recommendation-16d","fullItemName":"Basis for recommendation","depth":3,"htmlHeader":"<!-- begin field 918b9461-6b74-4405-8857-43fbe2e76529 --><h3>Basis for recommendation</h3><!-- end field 918b9461-6b74-4405-8857-43fbe2e76529 -->","summary":null,"htmlStringContent":"<!-- begin item 16dad2bb-1073-43d7-b65a-b02155124cd7 --><!-- begin field 229fe7b1-7e8d-4cc8-aa85-c84a6b16a747 --><p>Recommendations on assessment of a person with suspected pubic lice are based on the clinical guidelines <em>Canadian guidelines on sexually transmitted infections. Management and treatment of specific infections - ectoparasitic infestations</em> [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/pubic-lice/references/\">Public Health Agency of Canada, 2013</a>], <em>Sexually transmitted infections in primary care</em> [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/pubic-lice/references/\">RCGP, 2013</a>], 2015 <em>Sexually transmitted diseases treatment guidelines. Ectoparasitic infections: pediculosis pubis</em> [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/pubic-lice/references/\">CDC, 2015</a>],<em> Pubic lice</em> [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/pubic-lice/references/\">Primary Care Dermatology Society, 2015</a>], and <em>European guideline for the management of pediculosis pubis</em> [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/pubic-lice/references/\">Salavastru, 2017</a>] and expert opinion in review articles [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/pubic-lice/references/\">Gunning, 2012</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/pubic-lice/references/\">Markova, 2014</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/pubic-lice/references/\">Dadabhoy, 2015</a>].</p><h4>Ask about other sexually transmitted infections (STIs)</h4><ul><li>Sexual contact is a common mode of pubic lice transmission and concomitant STIs have been found in up to 30% of people [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/pubic-lice/references/\">Markova, 2014</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/pubic-lice/references/\">Salavastru, 2017</a>].</li></ul><h4>Examine other hairy areas of the body</h4><ul><li>If pubic lice are identified, all coarse body hair (such as eyebrows, eyelashes, beard, axillae, abdomen, chest and scalp margins) should be examined as lice can also colonise these areas [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/pubic-lice/references/\">Primary Care Dermatology Society, 2015</a>].</li></ul><!-- end field 229fe7b1-7e8d-4cc8-aa85-c84a6b16a747 --><!-- end item 16dad2bb-1073-43d7-b65a-b02155124cd7 -->","subChapters":[]}]}}},"staticQueryHashes":["3666801979"]}